tables.description: The audit_checks table represents a record of audits performed across various sites. It stores information about the audit date, auditor, and audit score, which are crucial for tracking compliance and quality standards. This table is typically used in analytics and business workflows to identify trends, areas of improvement, and to make informed decisions about resource allocation.

columns.description: The audit_pk column represents a unique identifier for each audit record, enabling the organization to track and manage audits efficiently. It stores an integer value, which is used to link related audit records and to facilitate data analysis. This column is crucial for tracking compliance and quality standards.

The site_fk column represents the site affiliation for each audit record, enabling the organization to track audits performed across different sites. It stores an integer value, which is used to link related audit records and to facilitate data analysis. This column is important for identifying trends and areas of improvement across different sites.

The audit_dt column represents the date on which each audit was performed, enabling the organization to track audit schedules and to identify trends over time. It stores a date value, which is used to facilitate data analysis and to inform decision-making processes. This column is crucial for tracking compliance and quality standards.

The auditor column represents the individual responsible for conducting each audit, enabling the organization to track audit personnel and to identify areas of expertise. It stores a character varying value, which is used to facilitate data analysis and to inform decision-making processes. This column is important for identifying trends and areas of improvement in audit quality.

The audit_score column represents the score achieved by each audit, enabling the organization to track compliance and quality standards. It stores an integer value, which is used to facilitate data analysis and to inform decision-making processes. This column is crucial for identifying areas of improvement and for making informed decisions about resource allocation.
